Package com.phasmidsoftware.dsaipg.util.benchmark

Class Benchmark_Timer<T>

java.lang.Object
com.phasmidsoftware.dsaipg.util.benchmark.Benchmark_Timer<T>
Type Parameters:
T - The generic type T is that of the input to the function f which you will pass in to the constructor.
All Implemented Interfaces:
Benchmark<T>
Direct Known Subclasses:
BSTBenchmark, SorterBenchmark
public class Benchmark_Timer<T> extends Object implements Benchmark<T>
This class implements a simple Benchmark utility for measuring the running time of algorithms. It is part of the repository for the INFO6205 class, taught by Prof. Robin Hillyard

It requires Java 8 as it uses function types, in particular, UnaryOperator<T> (a function of T => T), Consumer<T> (essentially a function of T => Void) and Supplier<T> (essentially a function of Void => T).

In general, the benchmark class handles three phases of a "run:"

  1. The pre-function which prepares the input to the study function (field fPre) (may be null);
  2. The study function itself (field fRun) -- assumed to be a mutating function since it does not return a result;
  3. The post-function which cleans up and/or checks the results of the study function (field fPost) (may be null).

Note that the clock does not run during invocations of the pre-function and the post-function (if any).

    • Benchmark_Timer

      public Benchmark_Timer(String description, UnaryOperator<T> fPre, Consumer<T> fRun, Consumer<T> fPost)
      Constructor for a Benchmark_Timer with the option of specifying all three functions.
      Parameters:
      description - the description of the benchmark.
      fPre - a function of T => T. Function fPre is run before each invocation of fRun (but with the clock stopped). The result of fPre (if any) is passed to fRun.
      fRun - a Consumer function (i.e. a function of T => Void). Function fRun is the function whose timing you want to measure. For example, you might create a function which sorts an array. When you create a lambda defining fRun, you must return "null."
      fPost - a Consumer function (i.e. a function of T => Void).
